{
  "answer": "**\"Hwaer cwom maththumgyfa?\"** (Where is the treasure-giver?).[^1]\n\nThis question about the lost *mathþumgyfa*—a kenning for a generous lord or treasure-giver in the mead-hall—immediately follows in the lamenting speech (lines 92–93), part of the *ubi sunt* (\"where are they?\") passage contrasting past glory with present ruin.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Old English Elegies, *The Wanderer* [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/transliteration/#p-2ecb4b).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., translation: \"...Where has the horse gone? Where has the warrior gone? **Where the treasure-giver?** ...\" [chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/).\n\n[^3]: The full chapter is one continuous poetic paragraph in the transliteration (p-2ecb4b), with the phrase at ~lines 92–93. The image evokes vanished aristocratic bounty, heightening the theme of loss before further questions about feast-seats (*symbla gesetu*) and exclamations (*Eala beorht bune!*, \"Alas, bright cup!\").",
